China Stocks: Xi’An Aircraft, Anhui Conch, Xiamen Faratronic

-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 
2011-08-04T03:08:31Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-03/bocom-gd-power-gree-electric-petrochina-china-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in  China  trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses
and prices are as of 10:45 a.m. local time.  The Shanghai Composite Index, which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, rose 0.5 percent to 2,691.71. The  CSI
300 Index (SHSZ300)  advanced 0.6 percent to 2,973.46.  Aircraft and component makers:  Xi’An Aircraft International
Corp. (000768)  (000768 CH) rose for a third day, gaining 2.1 percent to
11.43 yuan. Jiangxi Hongdu Aviation Industry Co. (600316 CH)
gained 3.2 percent to 33.22 yuan.  China will set up a development fund for the nation’s civil
aircraft industry, Shanghai Securities News reported today,
without saying where it got the information. The government will
designate aircraft manufacturing as one the nation’s strategic
industries and will give legislation and fiscal support,
according to the newspaper.  Huaxin Cement Co. (600801 CH) climbed 1.8 percent to 26.53
yuan, set for the highest close since July 25. Anhui Conch
Cement Co. (600585 CH), the nation’s biggest building material
maker, gained 1.1 percent to 25.81 yuan.  China’s cement makers had a combined profit of 35.2 billion
yuan in the first five months, up 170 percent from the same
period a year earlier, the Ministry of Industry and  Information
Technology  said in a statement yesterday. The average cement
price per ton rose 57.24 yuan in June from a year earlier,
according to the statement.  Xiamen Faratronic Co. (600563 CH) jumped 4.3 percent to
24.82 yuan, heading for its biggest gain since July 11. The
company’s net income increased 38 percent to 152.8 million yuan
in the first six months, according to a statement to the
 Shanghai Stock Exchange .  To contact the reporters on this story: Irene Shen in Shanghai
at   ishen4@bloomberg.net ; Helen Yuan in
Shanghai at   hyuan@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
